## The Week at a Glance

- 🔴 **High — Active credential theft campaign targeting your employees.** Microsoft has documented ACR Stealer attacks using convincing on-screen prompts to trick employees into handing over browser credentials and authentication tokens. This is happening now, across enterprise environments.
- 🔴 **High — Exchange Server 2016 and 2019 reach final end-of-support in October 2026.** Microsoft has confirmed there will be no further extensions. Organizations still running on-premises Exchange on these versions have roughly 90 days to migrate or accept the risk of running unpatched email infrastructure.
- 🟡 **Medium — Advanced Intune device management capabilities are now included in your existing Microsoft 365 E3 and E5 licenses.** Capabilities your organization may have been paying extra for, or going without, are now available at no additional cost. A licensing review is warranted.
- 🟢 **Low — Microsoft Entra Backup and Recovery is now generally available.** Your identity directory, including user accounts, Conditional Access policies, and group memberships, can now be automatically backed up and restored after accidental or malicious changes.

*Sources: [Microsoft Security Blog – ACR Stealer](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/16/acr-stealer-two-observed-intrusion-chains-amid-increased-threat-activity/) · [Exchange Team Blog – ESU End Date](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/reminder-exchange-2016-and-2019-esu-program-ends-in-october-2026/ba-p/4539033) · [Intune Blog – E3/E5 Packaging](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-intune-blog/advanced-microsoft-intune-capabilities-now-available-in/ba-p/4529335)*

---

## Why This Week Matters

Two of this week's most significant items share a common thread: organizations that delay decisions on known risks tend to absorb those risks at the worst possible moment. The ACR Stealer campaign is active now, and Exchange's final support deadline is fixed and confirmed. Beyond the immediate pressures, Microsoft's broader announcements this week reflect an accelerating shift toward governing AI agents with the same rigor applied to human employees, a challenge most organizations have not yet formally addressed. The one thing leadership must understand: AI tools and agents are now a data security perimeter, and the policies, controls, and governance structures that protect your business need to extend to cover them.

*Sources: [Microsoft Security Blog – ACR Stealer](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/16/acr-stealer-two-observed-intrusion-chains-amid-increased-threat-activity/) · [Microsoft Entra Blog – AI Agent Governance](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-entra-blog/govern-ai-agent-identities-and-access-the-same-way-you-govern/ba-p/4529302)*

