## What Your Employees Will Notice

- **Sign-in experience is changing.** Microsoft is making passkeys the default authentication method in Entra ID and adjusting how SMS and voice verification work. Employees will be prompted to set up passkeys. Those who use SMS codes to log in today may notice changes to that flow. Proactive communication before this reaches your workforce will reduce confusion and helpdesk calls.
- **Copilot is now running on GPT-5.6.** OpenAI's latest model is now powering Microsoft 365 Copilot in Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Chat, and Cowork. Employees using Copilot daily may notice improved reasoning on complex, multi-step tasks. No action is required; the change is automatic.
- **Message Recall now works across organizations.** Senders can now recall emails sent to recipients at other companies, not just within your own tenant. Employees should understand that a recalled message generates a notification to the recipient. This does not make recall invisible.
- **Remote desktop sessions on Windows 365 or Azure Virtual Desktop are more reliable.** A networking improvement called RDP Multipath with redundant TCP is now live. Employees working on Cloud PCs who experienced dropped sessions or stuttering in restrictive network environments should see improvement without taking any action.

*Sources: [Microsoft Security Blog – Passkeys Default](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/13/microsoft-entra-id-security-updates-passkeys-are-the-default-authentication-method-in-entra-id/) · [Exchange Team Blog – Cross-Tenant Message Recall](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/cross-tenant-message-recall-in-exchange-online/ba-p/4535800) · [Microsoft 365 Copilot Blog – GPT-5.6](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-365-copilot-blog/available-today-openai-s-gpt-5-6-in-microsoft-365-copilot/ba-p/4533152)*

---

## What Your Help Desk Should Expect

- **Passkey enrollment questions and authentication failures.** As Microsoft rolls out passkeys as the default, expect employees to contact the helpdesk when unfamiliar prompts appear during sign-in. Prepare your helpdesk team with a simple explanation and a guided enrollment path. Volume may be significant if no proactive communication goes out first.
- **ACR Stealer-related account compromise reports.** Given the active campaign, your helpdesk should treat any reports of unexpected sign-in prompts, locked accounts, or suspicious browser behavior as potentially related to credential theft. Escalation paths to your security team should be pre-defined and ready.
- **Message Recall confusion.** Employees who recall emails sent to external recipients will generate notifications on the receiving end. Expect inbound questions from employees who received such notifications and are unsure what happened, as well as from senders wondering whether the recall succeeded.
- **Passkey compatibility questions from remote or shared-device users.** Passkeys tie to a specific device or authenticator. Employees who rotate between shared workstations or who use personal devices for work may face complications. Help desk staff need guidance on approved workarounds.

*Sources: [Microsoft Security Blog – Passkeys Default](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/13/microsoft-entra-id-security-updates-passkeys-are-the-default-authentication-method-in-entra-id/) · [Microsoft Security Blog – ACR Stealer](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/16/acr-stealer-two-observed-intrusion-chains-amid-increased-threat-activity/) · [Exchange Team Blog – Cross-Tenant Message Recall](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/cross-tenant-message-recall-in-exchange-online/ba-p/4535800)*

