## If You Take No Action

**ACR Stealer credential theft campaign:** Employees are actively being targeted with convincing browser prompts designed to harvest their passwords and authentication tokens. If your organization does not reinforce phishing-resistant authentication and issue targeted awareness guidance, compromised credentials will go undetected until an attacker uses them. The downstream consequences include unauthorized access to email, files, and connected systems, potential regulatory notification obligations, and cyber insurance claims scrutiny if MFA was not properly enforced.

**Exchange Server 2016 and 2019 reaching end of support in October 2026:** After October 31, any vulnerability discovered in these products will never be patched. Organizations running email on these servers will be permanently exposed to any exploit developed after that date. This is not a theoretical future risk. Exchange has been among the most targeted enterprise products in recent years. Regulators and cyber insurers both scrutinize end-of-life software. The window to complete migration on a planned schedule rather than an emergency one is closing.

**AI agents operating without formal identity governance:** If AI agents in your environment are using shared credentials, unscoped access, or no formal identity at all, they represent an access risk that falls outside your existing monitoring and audit frameworks. A compromised or misbehaving agent with broad access and no assigned identity is difficult to detect, contain, or attribute. As agent use scales, the governance gap scales with it.

